We have exciting machines that can take us into space - 2.5 million parts in five years.
On the other hand, if we look at natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that can be folded up in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
This is the complexity of our natural systems, but they are very efficient, more efficient than anything we can build and more complex than anything we can build.
They are more efficient in energy.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can repair themselves and maintain a long life.
There is a very interesting thing about natural systems.
If we can transform it into our built environment, the way we construct things will have great potential.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all the complexity of what we want to build - that is, our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences - basically the DNA of the operation of our buildings.
Then we need a programmable part that can accept the sequence and be used for folding or remodeling.
We need some energy to activate so that our parts can be folded up according to the program.
We need some types of error-correcting redundancy to ensure that what we successfully build is what we want.
